04255nam a22007335i 9780674275157DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742751577 a10.4159/97806742751572doi  a(DE-B1597)613885  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHQ536b.M412 2006 7aLAW0380002bisacsh04a306.8/09732221 aMcClain, Linda C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Place of Families :bFostering Capacity, Equality, and Responsibility /cLinda C. McClain. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Fostering Capacity -- t1 The Place of Families and Government in a Formative Project -- t2 Families as “Seedbeds of Civic Virtue”? -- t3 Care, Families, and Self-Government -- tII Fostering Equality -- t4 Marriage Promotion, Marriage (E)quality, and Welfare Reform -- t5 Recognizing Same-Sex Marriage -- t6 Beyond Marriage? -- tIII Fostering Responsibility -- t7 Rights, (Ir)responsibility, and Reproduction -- t8 Teaching Sexual and Reproductive Responsibility -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this bold new book, Linda McClain offers a liberal and feminist theory of the relationships between family life and politics--a topic dominated by conservative thinkers. McClain agrees that stable family lives are vital to forming persons into capable, responsible, self-governing citizens. But what are the public values at stake when we think about families, and what sorts of families should government recognize and promote? Arguing that family life helps create the virtues and character required for citizenship, McClain shows that the connection between family self-government and democratic self-government does not require the deep-laid gender inequality that has historically accompanied it. Examining controversial issues in family law and policy--among them, the governmental promotion of heterosexual marriage and the denial of marriage to same-sex couples, the regulation of family life through welfare policy, and constitutional rights to reproductive freedom--McClain argues for a political theory of the family that embraces equality, defends rights as facilitating responsibility, and supports families in ways that respect men's and women's capacities for self-government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCivics. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aFamiliesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aFamily policyzUnited States. 0aFeminist theory. 0aMarriagexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 7aLAW / Family Law / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674275157zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674275157423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674275157/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK